│ (-x)` is miscompiling when `x` is a `select` and the original subtraction has the `nsw`    │
│ (no signed wrap) flag. The reproducer demonstrates this with `sub i8 %y, (select i1 %c, i8 │
│ %x, i8 %t0)`, where `%t0` is `sub nsw i8 0, %x`. The optimizer sinks the negation into the │
│ `select`, yielding `add i8 %y, (select i1 %c, i8 %t0, i8 %x)`. \n\nThe problem occurs when │
│ `%x` is `-128` (`0x80` for `i8`). The initial negation `sub nsw i8 0, %x` results in       │
│ `poison` because negating the minimum signed integer causes signed overflow. \n\n- In the  │
│ **source IR**, if `%c` is true, the `select` chooses `%x` (`-128`), and the final result   │
│ is valid.\n- In the **target IR**, if `%c` is true, the `select` (with its arms swapped by │
│ the negation) chooses `%t0`, which is `poison`. This makes the entire expression           │
│ `poison`.\n\nThis makes the transformed code more poisonous than the source, which is a    │
│ violation of optimizer rules.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` debug log       │
